<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1886-05-18T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1886-05-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="21" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d21">
                    <head>No. 21.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Bayard</persName>
                            to Mr. <persName type="to">Tree</persName>.</hi></head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1886-05-18"><hi rend="italic">May</hi> 18,
                            1886</date>.</dateline>
                        <seg rendition="#left">No. 43.]</seg></opener>
                    <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Your despatch No. 89, of the 6th instant, in
                        which you state that the Commission appointed on the condition of industrial
                        labor in Belgium has organized and commenced its sessions, has been
                        received. I shall be much obliged to you for reports as to the proceedings
                        of the Commission, and as to the conclusion reached by it.</p>
                    <p>I am, sir, &amp;c.,</p>
                    <closer><signed>T. F. BAYARD.</signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>